{
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Overview",
      "content": "Biliary tract cancers harbor clinically relevant genomic alterations that differ by anatomic subsite. Tumor genomic profiling is recommended for patients with unresectable or metastatic BTCs. Key events include:"
    },
    {
      "heading": "FGFR2 fusions",
      "content": "- **FGFR2 gene fusions/rearrangements**: Found in approximately 9%–15% of intrahepatic CCAs and are rare in other subsites. These lead to constitutive activation of FGFR signaling, promoting cell proliferation and tumorigenesis. Targetable by pemigatinib, futibatinib, and erdafitinib [BIL-B 5 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-29]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "IDH1 mutations",
      "content": "- **IDH1 mutations**: Occur in approximately 10%–20% of intrahepatic CCAs and are rare in other subsites. Mutations (most commonly at codon 132, R132X) lead to accumulation of the oncometabolite 2-hydroxyglutarate, impairing cellular differentiation. Targetable by ivosidenib [BIL-B 5 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-29]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "BRAF V600E",
      "content": "- **BRAF V600E mutations**: Present in approximately 1%–5% of BTCs. This mutation results in constitutive activation of the MAPK signaling pathway. Targetable by dabrafenib/trametinib [BIL-B 4 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-28]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "NTRK fusions",
      "content": "- **NTRK1/2/3 gene fusions**: Estimated to occur in <1% of BTCs. These fusions lead to expression of oncogenic TRK fusion proteins. Targetable by larotrectinib, entrectinib, and repotrectinib [BIL-B 4 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-26]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "MSI-H/dMMR",
      "content": "- **MSI-H/dMMR**: Present in approximately 1%–3% of BTCs. Results from deficient DNA mismatch repair. Predicts response to immune checkpoint inhibitors like pembrolizumab [BIL-B 4 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-26]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "TMB-H",
      "content": "- **TMB-H**: Found in <5% of advanced BTCs. Predicts response to immune checkpoint inhibitors [BIL-B 3 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-27]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "HER2 alterations",
      "content": "- **HER2 (ERBB2) overexpression/amplification/activating mutations**: Present in approximately 5%–20% of CCAs and 15%–30% of gallbladder cancers. A member of the ErbB/EGFR family that activates downstream proliferative pathways. Targetable by trastuzumab deruxtecan, pertuzumab/trastuzumab, tucatinib/trastuzumab, and zanidatamab [BIL-B 6 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-30]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "NRG1 fusions",
      "content": "- **NRG1 gene fusions**: Found in <1% of BTCs, more commonly in iCCA and eCCA. Targetable by zenocutuzumab-zbco [BIL-B 6 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "KRAS G12C",
      "content": "- **KRAS G12C mutation**: Reported in about 1% of BTCs. Targetable by adagrasib [BIL-B 6 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-32]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "RET fusions",
      "content": "- **RET gene fusions**: Rare (<1%). Targetable by pralsetinib and selpercatinib [BIL-B 6 of 8, BIL-C 3 of 5, MS-32]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Inherited syndromes",
      "content": "Additionally, up to 10%–15% of BTCs may be associated with inherited cancer predisposition syndromes. Germline alterations in high- to moderate-penetrance genes like BRCA1/2, MLH1, MSH2, PALB2, and ATM have been identified in roughly 9%–11% of cases [BIL-B 1 of 8, MS-25]."
    }
  ],
